The light weight firing pin transmits the energy of the hammer to ignite the primer. The functioning of the mechanism surpasses all applicable SAAMI safety standards. The grip is made of the ultra high impact polymer DuPont ST-8018. The grip also forms the magazine well and the trigger guard. Normally supplied with a 10-round double column all steel magazine.

title: For Sale:  1886 Steyr Kropatschek RARE (1 of 4000) Carbine (20inch) Exc. Bore, Nice Gun NO FFL
postcontent: This is one of the elusive carbines made by Steyr for the horseback units of Portugal. Caliber is 8x60Rmm and only 4000 made and from what I found, 1200 came to the US. No import marks and this is a cool gun. A magazine tube under the barrel holds 4 or 5 in the carbine, I forget, and the elevator system works like new, as does everything on this gun. Has the cleaning rod, and all parts, plus a nice trigger. The bore is great with fine rifling and minor wear but no rust, no pitting and that goes for the exterior too. Faded finish yes, but the receiver has nice color and parts of the barrel have some color but NO corrosion or pitting. These guns used ammo that was black powder for the 1st 10 years so it is amazing how nice it is inside. I also have a short rifle (26 inch) which is also rare as they made 4600. The more common long rifles (32 inch) are found for sale but very rarely do you see a short rifle and a carbine together, so you can have the whole Portugese triad. The Portugese seriously cared for their weapons as 130 years later, the bore and action are nicer than almost every Mosin I had that are from the 1930s and 40s. I have a full set of photos I can send you if interested. Decent long rifles sell for $375 to $450 and I can not find a record of a true carbine sold anywhere recently, but I will list the short rifle (26 inch barrel and 4400 made) at $475 and the carbine (20 inch barrel 4000 made) at $550. THIS LISTING IS FOR THE CARBINE  All carbines have a turned down bolt

title: For Sale/Trade:  Beretta 950BS .25acp Jetfire
postcontent:
Alright folks, I am throwing in the towel on this one.

A little backstory, I have always wanted a Beretta 950 Jetfire, 25 ACP, but had never found one in the condition I have wanted (I.E. good bluing, like new).  Well, as of a few weeks ago I found one on Armslist that looked great, catch 22 is it was in a different state.  Anyways, I paid the guy and had it shipped.  The long and short of it is that it does not work.  I will tell you what I know:

The hammer when I got the gun was difficult to retract.  I foolishly attributed this to the gun just being excessively dry and took it home.  After lubing it the hammer freed up slightly and I took it to the range.  At the range the hammer failed to properly strike one out of every five rounds.  When I got home I tore the gun down and pulled all the components out of the gun.  The inside of the frame shows excessive wear against the right side of the hammer.  The roll pin that the hammer rides on was bent.  I figured I was only dealing with a bent roll pin and decided to order a new one.  After installing the new one, the problem is no better, and I would say perhaps worse.  Given that a new (straight) pin made the hammer harder to move I have come to the conclusion that it is either the hammer, or the frame that the problem resides in. That said I am not a gunsmith, only reasonably experienced in diagnosing problems in anything mechanical.  

So, I am selling the gun.  If the gun is fixable, you I think will have a nice gun, if it is not, you have a bunch of parts for a 950.  I am fairly certain it is fixable, and a competent pistol smith could fix it up.  I am just unwilling to invest any more money into it.  It is up for $100, or I will trade for 250 rounds of factory .45 ACP.  I am taking a bath on it but I chalk it up to a life lesson that I figured I might get burned on when I did it.  If you would like it for parts or want to try and fix it up, I'm letting it go for a very reasonable price.

It is for sale in the Knoxville area.
